, but it may originally have been a similar formation deriving from the common medieval given name   Annis  , a vernacular form of   Agnes .  Nowadays it is an independent name, and was especially popular in America in the 1930s, 40s, and 50s."]},{"name":"Nan","meanings":["Originally a pet form of   Ann   (for the initial <i>N-</i>,  compare  Ned  ). It is now also widely used as a short form of   Nancy ."]}]},{"name":"Seymour","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, originally a Norman baronial name from <i>Saint-Maur</i> in Normandy. This place was so called from the dedication of its church to St <i>Maurus</i> (  compare  Maurice  )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"St","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Cornish: A Cornish form of Just (Prouter Est, the priest of St. Just)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Maur","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin.  St Maura  was a 5th-century martyr, of whom very little is known; her companion is variously named as <i>Britta</i> (of Celtic origin) and <i>Baya</i> (of Latin origin). In Ireland <i>Maura</i> is now commonly regarded as a form of   Mary ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mauro","meanings":["From Latin <i>Maurus</i> ‘Moor’, i.e. ‘swarthy’; the name of one of the earliest followers of St Benedict."]}]},{"name":"Saint","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cyr, Remy.","English and French: nickname for a particularly pious individual, from Old French and Middle English <i>saint(e)</i>, <i>seint(e)</i> ‘holy’ (from Latin <i>sanctus</i> ‘blameless, holy’). The vocabulary word was occasionally used in the Middle Ages as a personal name and this may have given rise to some instances of the surname.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone who wore, made, or sold girdles, from Middle English <i>ceint</i>, <i>seint</i>, <i>saint</i> ‘girdle’ (Old French <i>ceint</i>, Latin <i>cinctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Center","meanings":["English and Scottish (Aberdeenshire): metonymic occupational name from Middle English, Old French <i>ceinture</i>, <i>seinture</i> ‘girdle’, denoting someone who made or sold girdles, or perhaps a nickname for someone who wore a distinctive girdle.","English: variant of   Senter   1.","Americanized form of German   Zehnder   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Sant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Krishan, Anagha, Anjali, Arvind, Deepak, Milind, Nilima, Ravindra, Sanjeev, Sanjiv, Vasudev.","English (Cheshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Saint  .","Italian (northeastern): variant of   Santo  ."]},{"name":"Sante","meanings":["name bestowed in honour of the medieval poet  Dante Alighieri  (  1265–1321 ), also used in the English-speaking world. As a medieval given name <i>Dante</i> was a contracted form of <i>Durante</i> ‘steadfast, enduring’. In an English context it was famously borne by the pre-Raphaelite poet and painter  Dante Gabriel Rossetti  (  1828–1882 ), the son of an exiled Italian scholar and patriot."]}]},{"name":"More","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A Welsh name derived from mawr, great."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Anne Seymour St Maur Saint More Stowell was born in 1480. She had at least 2 sons and 3 daughters with Robert Stawell."},"et":{"1480–":"1480–Surnud","1476–1508":"1476–1508","1482–Female":"1482–Surnud","1489–Male":"1489–Surnud","1490–Male":"1490–Surnud","1491–Female":"1491–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","about 1491":"umbes 1491","Abt 1482":"umbes 1482","about 1490":"umbes 1490","1489":"1489","abt. 1489":"umbes 1489","1476":"1476","1482":"1482","1508":"1508","1480":"1480","1491":"1491","1490":"1490","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, U